{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is dollar-cost averaging?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Dollar-cost averaging (DCA) means investing a fixed dollar amount on a fixed schedule — say $500 every month — regardless of what the market is doing. Because the amount is fixed, you automatically buy more shares when prices are low and fewer when prices are high, which pulls your average cost per share below the average market price over the period."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does dollar-cost averaging beat lump-sum investing?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Usually not. Because markets rise more often than they fall, money invested earlier is usually worth more than money invested later — studies by Vanguard and others find a day-one lump sum ends higher roughly two-thirds of the time over 6-12 month deployment windows. DCA wins when the market falls during the deployment period, and it meaningfully reduces worst-case outcomes and regret. It's insurance against bad timing, and insurance has a cost."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should I invest when dollar-cost averaging?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Frequency matters far less than consistency. Weekly, biweekly, and monthly schedules produce nearly identical long-run results because short-interval price differences are small and random. Most investors settle on monthly to match their paycheck, which also minimizes transaction overhead. What destroys DCA results isn't the wrong frequency — it's pausing contributions when markets get scary."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is investing from every paycheck the same as dollar-cost averaging?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Mechanically yes, conceptually no. True DCA is choosing to spread out money you already have. Paycheck investing — like 401(k) contributions — invests money as fast as you receive it, which is actually lump-sum investing on a rolling basis. If you're investing from income, you're already doing the optimal thing. The DCA-vs-lump-sum debate only applies when you're sitting on cash you could deploy today."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What volatility number should I use?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Around 15% annual volatility is typical for a broad, diversified stock index like the S&P 500 over long periods. A 60/40 stock-bond portfolio runs closer to 9-10%; an aggressive single-sector or small-cap portfolio can exceed 20%; individual stocks and crypto are far higher. Set volatility to 0 to see the smooth flat-rate projection most calculators show — then raise it to see how wide real outcomes actually spread."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does this calculator model volatility?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It runs 500 Monte Carlo simulations: each one draws random per-interval returns from a log-normal distribution calibrated to your expected annual return (treated as the long-run compound growth rate) and your chosen volatility. The chart shows the median path and the 10th-90th percentile band across those simulated markets, and the lump-sum comparison reuses the same 500 markets so both strategies face identical conditions. A fixed random seed keeps results reproducible."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is dollar-cost averaging good in a bear market?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Falling markets are where DCA shines. Every scheduled purchase buys shares at a lower price than the last, dragging your average cost down, so a smaller recovery gets you back to break-even — and positions you for larger gains when prices normalize. The catch: nobody knows they're in the early stage of a bear market except in hindsight, which is why committing to the schedule matters more than predicting the market."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does dollar-cost averaging reduce risk?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It reduces timing risk — the chance of investing everything at a peak — by spreading purchases across many prices. It narrows the range of outcomes: worse best-case, better worst-case. It does not reduce market risk once you're invested; after the deployment period ends, your portfolio rides the same volatility either way. DCA is a strategy for getting in, not a permanent shield."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a cost basis line?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Your cost basis is the total amount you've contributed so far — the money you put in, before any growth. On this calculator's chart it's the stepped line climbing steadily as contributions land. When the portfolio value line sits above the cost basis line, you're in profit; below it, you're underwater. Watching the gap between the two lines is the clearest way to see compounding take over from saving."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I dollar-cost average a windfall or inheritance?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "This is the classic DCA decision. The math favors investing it all immediately — markets rise more often than they fall. The psychology often favors spreading it over 6-12 months: if the market drops 20% the week after you invest a life-changing sum, will you panic-sell? If yes, DCA's insurance is worth the expected cost. Choose a fixed schedule, automate it, and never extend it based on market headlines."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why does the lump sum usually win in this calculator?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Because the lump sum puts the full amount to work on day one, while DCA holds part of the money in cash during the deployment window. With a positive expected return, more time invested means more expected growth. At a realistic 6-12 month deployment window, that's worth roughly two-thirds of simulated markets at stock-like assumptions — matching the well-known Vanguard research — regardless of how far out you forecast afterward, since both strategies simply hold once DCA finishes deploying. Stretch the deployment window itself out to years instead of months and the win rate climbs much higher, but at that point it's no longer a real windfall-timing decision — it's just comparing money you have now to money you'd save gradually later. Also check the 10th percentile outcomes, where DCA's damage control shows up."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does dollar-cost averaging work for crypto or single stocks?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The mechanics work on anything with a price, and the case for DCA is actually stronger for highly volatile assets — timing risk is bigger when swings are bigger. But DCA can't fix a bad asset: averaging into something that goes to zero just means losing money in installments. DCA manages when you buy; it says nothing about whether the thing is worth buying. Diversification does that job."
      }
    }
  ]
}
